The German #wasp is a global invader. A study by Eloff et al. analyzed population genetics in their invaded South African range. They concluded that they maintain a homogenous population with individual movement between localities. Read the article at https://rdcu.be/b1umO!

Stinging insects: The two most common species of wasps in the Sacramento area are Vespula pensylvanica (common wasp) and Vespula germanica (German wasp). German wasps make their nests in walls or attics, which can cause structural damage.

For #WorldWaspDay I bring to you a wasp I am not very fond of. The German Wasp Vespula germanica. This wasp was introduced after WW2 and preys on invertebrates and is serious competition with honeybees and native birds for both nectar and honeydew in New Zealand. #entomology

Many Ivy patches attract good numbers of both Common Wasp (worker 1, male 2) and German Wasp (worker 3, male 4). Notice the narrow yellow shoulder stripe of former species & the paler yellow abdominal bands (often much narrower). German Wasp looks richer yellow & a little larger.

German Wasp (Vespula germanica) on Ivy flower. So subdued when they are feeding on this plant. Check out your local Ivy flower, the variety of insects attracted to it is staggering on a warm October day, once you witnessed you‚Äôll never clear the Ivy again, just so fascinating.
